    <node id="1. The question asks if the Canadian government will consider the climate emergency as a priority when developing its economic recovery plan for the ongoing pandemic.&#10;2. In response to this question, Hon. Jonathan Wilkinson (Minister of Environment and Climate Change) stated that while the immediate focus is on combatting the virus and easing some measures, the government recognizes the need to learn from this crisis and plan for future looming crises like climate change. He mentioned the intention to reflect on resilience for the economy as they move forward.&#10;3. Therefore, it can be inferred that the government will likely consider incorporating measures addressing the climate emergency in their economic recovery plan, although specific details have not been provided." />
    <node id="Minister of Small Business, Export Promotion and International Trade)&#10;Content: I want to thank the hon. member for the question. Small businesses are indeed incredibly important to all of our communities across the country. That is why we have implemented many measures to help them weather this difficult period in COVID-19. Whether it is a small business loan, a wage subsidy or commercial rent assistance, or just lowering the cost by deferring GST or HST or customs duties, many measures have been put forward to help our small businesses through this very difficult time.&#10;Speaker: The Acting Chair (Mrs. Alexandra Mends)&#10;Content: Mr. Manly, you may have a very short question.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Paul Manly&#10;Content: Thank you, Madam Chair. As we navigate this pandemic crisis, we are also in the middle of another major crisis: the climate emergency. Will this government develop its economic recovery plan for the pandemic with the climate emergency at the forefront of its planning?&#10;Speaker: The Acting Chair (Mrs. Alexandra Mends)&#10;Content: The hon. minister has 15 seconds.&#10;Speaker: Hon. Jonathan Wilkinson (Minister of Environment and Climate Change)&#10;Content: Thank you for the" />
