    <edge source="&#10;Content: My question referred to La Loche, but this is a broader issue. There are many work camps, including here in our north, that first nations are extremely concerned about. Will your government step in to support their calls for temporary shutdowns at this time?&#10;Speaker: Hon. Marc Miller&#10;Content: One of the things we see as we see the evolving dynamic and the potential spreads, particularly the fear of clusters as communities, provinces, territories may choose to relax certain measures, is the need to have a more targeted approach as to how the economy reacts and deals with it, particularly in northern and vulnerable communities. This is something for which we will need to have a serious approach, with both the Minister of Natural Resources and also our provincial counterparts, to make sure that we aren't taking hasty measures to reopen the economy while we're trying to protectand this is our most important goalindigenous communities from getting exposed and spreading COVID-19.&#10;Speaker: Ms. Niki Ashton&#10;Content: Madam Chair, my question is for the Minister of Fisheries. Hundreds of fishers and their families here in Manitoba who work with the Freshwater Fish Marketing Corporation are desperately calling for emergency support. Many are calling on the federal government to also" target="The Canadian government has implemented several measures to assist the fish and seafood sector during the COVID-19 pandemic. These measures include:&#10;&#10;1. Making the Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) accessible for people who are seasonal workers in the fish and seafood sector.&#10;2. Allowing people who have run out of Fisher EI benefits to qualify for the CERB.&#10;3. Investing $62.5 million to support fish and seafood processors in meeting challenges caused by COVID-19.&#10;4. Indigenous harvesters can access $306 million in funding through Aboriginal Financial Institutions, which provides short-term interest-free loans and non-repayable contributions for Indigenous small and medium-sized businesses.&#10;5. The Canadian Northern Economic Development Agency has also made available $15 million in non-repayable support for businesses.&#10;&#10;The government is working with coastal communities, fishers, and fisheries to address their concerns and challenges caused by the pandemic. This includes developing measures to ensure resilience of the food system and enabling safe and efficient processing, storing, packaging, and distribution of fish and seafood products. The government recognizes the importance of the fishery for coastal communities' economies and cultures, and they are working on addressing all issues faced by the sector during these challenging times.">
